    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-06-24T01:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-06-24T01:00:00-05:00" n="931"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d931">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">641.0031/132: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in New Zealand</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Cox</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Wellington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-06-24T18:00:00+12:00"
                            >June 24, 1943—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received June 24—12:21 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>294. Department’s 182, June 14, 6 p.m.<note n="10" xml:id="d931fn10">See footnote
                        6, <ref target="#pg_1100">p. 1100</ref>.</note> New Zealand officials told
                    me on June 17 that Campbell (see Legation’s 180, April 5, noon<note n="11"
                        xml:id="d931fn11">Not printed.</note>), <pb facs="1112" n="1102"
                        xml:id="pg_1102"/> New Zealand representative at London meeting, had been
                    given no instructions due to the absence from Wellington of both Nash<note
                        n="12" xml:id="d931fn12">Walter Nash, New Zealand Minister in the United
                        States.</note> and Fraser.<note n="13" xml:id="d931fn13">Peter Fraser, Prime
                        Minister of New Zealand.</note> They observed that New Zealand’s post-war
                    interests revolved around overseas markets for its primary products. New Zealand
                    was also concerned regarding the implications contained in article VII of United
                    States–United Kingdom Mutual Aid Agreement. Nash told me today that he has been
                    too occupied to send as yet any directive to Campbell. He mentioned the renewal
                    of the Trade Agreements Act and that he would continue discussions when he
                    returns to Washington. Time of return still indefinite.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Cox</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
